thread.title: In search for felon, Salem police arrest twin brother
thread.title_full: In search for felon, Salem police arrest twin brother | OregonLive.com

author: Nuran Alteir | The Oregonian/OregonLive
title: In search for felon, Salem police arrest twin brother
text:
Cesar Munoz, 33 Salem Police Department While looking for a felon wanted on a parole violation, Salem police found and arrested his identical twin.
At about 11:30 a.m. Wednesday, authorities thought they spotted 33-year-old Cesar Munoz, wanted on a parole violation, at Lansing and Market Street Northeast. When officers tried to contact him, he ran into a nearby hotel.
Inside, police confronted the man in a fitness room where they discovered he was Saul Munoz, their parolee's twin brother.
"Unfortunately for Saul, he was found to be in possession of methamphetamine and a stolen pistol," Lt. Steve Birr, commander of special operations with Salem Police Department, wrote in a news release.
Saul Munoz was booked into the Marion County Correctional Facility on charges of being a felon in possession of a firearm, unlawful possession of methamphetamine, theft and interfering with a police office.
Police are still searching for Cesar Munoz, who is described as being 5-foot-11 and 185 pounds. Cesar Munoz is considered armed and dangerous, Birr said, and anyone who sees him should call 911.
According to court records, Cesar Munoz was last convicted in 2013 for unauthorized use of a vehicle, fleeing or attempting to elude police, and being a felon in possession of a firearm.
